<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">
  <teiHeader>
      <fileDesc><!--2024-10-04 ebb: I would find a place in the TEI Header to add the information about the stamp. 
         You could even indicate in the teiHeader the specific lines in the poem that it crosses if you use line numbers in attributes... -->
         <titleStmt>
            <title>Ballad of Booker T.</title>
         </titleStmt>
         <publicationStmt>
            <p><date>1941-06-01</date></p> <!--I thought what I could put in the date element would be strictly constrained, but I was able to write "June 1, 1941", not just the ISO date
            2023-10-04 ebb: Indeed, you only get the ISO-formatted date constraint if you add a when attribute on the date. Try it! 
            Why is it like that? Because often if you wrap a date element while transcribing someone else's representation of it, it's not an ISO date: it's June 1, 1941, or something like that. 
            The attribute value is the best place to provide an ISO-formatted datatype that you can use for machine processing. 
            -->
            <!--According to the TEI website, I should be able to place the pubPlace element under the publicationStmt element, but it's not letting me. When I try placing it as the first element under publicationStmt, it tells me it expects a "publisher" element first. It also doesn't say this on the TEI website. 
               I now see it isn't good enough to stick "publisher" in a "p" element, even though the error message I get says it should be in a "p" element. The rabbit hole continues.
            
            ebb: You have my deep sympathy with this particular frustration of figuring out what's allowed precisely where in these TEI Header elements. We know it's irritating. In fact we need 
            better examples in the Guidelines. We always need more and better examples, because that's where people really pick up how to do something in TEI.
            -->
         
         </publicationStmt>
         <sourceDesc>
            <p>Online transcript from the <orgName>Library of Virginia, Education and Outreach Division</orgName>.</p>
            <p>Photofacsimile of the final draft of the poem, <orgName>Library of Congress</orgName>.</p>
         </sourceDesc>
      </fileDesc>
  </teiHeader>
  <text>
     <front>
        <docTitle><titlePart>Ballad of Booker T.</titlePart></docTitle>
        <byline>by Langston Hughes</byline> <!--I see on the TEI website I can also use the element "docAuthor" instead of byline. They can be used together or not. 
           I'm curious, in what situation would I use both, or one versus the other?
        2023-10-04 ebb: Yes, this is a case where TEI shows you multiple ways to do something. I would use byline in the context of maybe a collection of texts where you might have multiple authors. 
        docAuthor is invented for title pages I think, and it's meant to indicate a single author of whole document.
        -->
     </front>
      <body>
         <l><persName>Booker T.</persName> <lb/> Was a practical man.</l><!-- The "l" element doesn't have to be contained by "p". Since this entire document is a poem and not prose, do I not need to use "p"?
         2023-10-04 ebb: In fact, you should not use <p> around a poem in TEI! Use the <lg> element for that: it means "line-group" or a grouping of lines. 
         
         -->
         <!--Something funny I noticed, there's two "lb" elements: a self-closing "line break" and a "line beginning" 
         2023-10-04 ebb: There should only be one <lb/>, and we recently revised its description to indicate that it means line-beginning! It's only self-closed in TEI.
         I'm not quite sure I understand how you're using it here... 
         
         I would use <l> to wrap the entire lines in the poem: each line is its own portion of the poem; that is, the lineation of this document is based on verse lines of the poem.
         
         -->
         <l>He said, Till the soil <lb/> And learn from the land.</l>
         <l>Let down your bucket <lb/> Where you are.</l>
         <l>Your fate is here <lb/> And not afar.</l>
         <l> To help yourself <lb/> And your fellow man, <lb/> Train your head, <lb/> Your heart, and your hand. </l>
         <l>For smartness alone's <lb/> Surely not meet— <lb/> If you haven't at the same time <lb/> Got something to eat.</l>
         <l>Thus at <placeName>Tuskegee</placeName> <lb/> He built a school <lb/> With book-learning there <lb/> And the workman's tool.</l>
         <l>He started out <lb/> In a simple way— <lb/> For yesterday <lb/> Was not today.</l> <!--I wasn't sure whether or not to count the lines that had these hyphens in them as two separate lines or one big one. Personally I decided to do one big one, but I'm curious if that matters or if there's a way to mark that somehow.-->
         <l>Sometimes he had <lb/> Compromise in his talk— <lb/> For a man must crawl <lb/> Before he can walk— <lb/> And in <placeName>Alabama</placeName> in '85 <lb/> A joker was lucky <lb/> To be alive.</l>
         <l>But <persName>Booker T.</persName> <lb/> Was nobody's fool: <lb/> You may carve a dream <lb/> With an humble tool.</l>
         <l>The tallest tower<lb/> Can tumble down <lb/> If it be not rooted <lb/> In solid ground.</l>
         <l>So, being a far-seeing <lb/> Practical man, <lb/> He said, Train your head,<lb/> Your heart, and your hand.</l>
         <l>Your fate is here <lb/> And not afar, <lb/> So let down your bucket <lb/> Where you are.</l>
      <closer>
         <signed>Langston Hughes</signed>
         <objectName>Final Draft,</objectName>
         <address>
            <addrLine>Hollow Hills Farm,</addrLine>
            <addrLine>Montery, California,</addrLine>
         </address>
         <dateline>June 1, 1941.</dateline>
      </closer>
      </body>
  </text>
</TEI>

<!--Honestly, after I formatted all the text, it occured to me that I really don't know how to encode the stamp on it. I can't find a way that I'm happy with. I tried using "metamark" but I feel that it intruded on the actualy poem too much. I saw there was also a "stamp" element, but I couldn't include text describing the stamp. Perhaps I could've encoded the actualy poem differently, by retaining the line breaks instead of marking them as elements?-->
